`None` is valid in annotations, so I believe it can be validly expressed as `None`. Such an option would not necessarily be useless, though it would be a little unusual.

For example:
```python
def callback(ctx, param, value):
    warnings.warn("got deprecated option --foo")
    return None

@click.option("--foo", cls=AnnotatedOption, type_annotation=None, hidden=True, callback=callback)
def myfunc(*, foo: None) -> None:
    ...
```

If `--foo` is deprecated, it's not _necessary_ to make its type `None`. The following nearly-equivalent thing is also fine:
```python
def callback(ctx, param, value):
    warnings.warn("got deprecated option --foo")
    return value

@click.option("--foo", hidden=True, callback=callback)
def myfunc(*, foo: str | None) -> None:
    ...
```

But since this is meant to be at the core of the click type checker, I wanted to account for the possibility.

