@abtink Yes this was intended and works fine with PSA, as I usually test using PSA before updates. This was intended to avoid fragmentation of code by using ifdefs. You are right `otMacKeyMaterial` is a union and in case of PSA, `GetKey` never returns `nullptr`. That is why, we are not validating `mKey` or `mKeyRef` in AES modules. we pass the otCryptoKey variable after initialising `mKeyRef` and `mKey`. And based on `OPENTHREAD_CONFIG_PLATFORM_KEY_REFERENCES_ENABLE`, either one of them will be invalid. It is upto the Crypto platform abstraction to use the correct member based on the implementation supported.

For example, the default mbedTLS implementation has this:
```
OT_TOOL_WEAK otError otPlatCryptoAesSetKey(void *aContext, size_t aContextSize, otCryptoKey *aKey)
{
    otError              error    = OT_ERROR_NONE;
    mbedtls_aes_context *mContext = static_cast<mbedtls_aes_context *>(aContext);

    VerifyOrExit(aContextSize >= sizeof(mbedtls_aes_context), error = OT_ERROR_FAILED);
    VerifyOrExit((mbedtls_aes_setkey_enc(mContext, aKey->mKey, (aKey->mKeyLength * CHAR_BIT)) == 0),
                 error = OT_ERROR_FAILED);

exit:
    return error;
}
```

As we know we want only the `mKey`, we ignore the mKeyRef. And in my PSA implementation I ignore the mKey, as I know we support PSA.

